{"query":"Voyager 1 Gliese 445 closest approach estimated years trajectory","follow_up_questions":null,"answer":null,"images":[],"results":[{"url":"https://mathscinotes.wordpress.com/2013/06/30/voyager-1-and-gliese-445","title":"Voyager 1 and Gliese 445 - Math Encounters Blog","content":"The closest Gliese 445 and Voyager 1 will get is about 1.7 light-years. My interest in these numbers was raised when I noticed that Voyager 1's","score":0.90289277,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://www.wionews.com/photos/in-40-000-years-voyager-1-will-brush-past-gliese-445-understanding-the-star-of-camelopardalis-1756938570662","title":"In 40,000 years, Voyager 1 will brush past Gliese 445, the star of Camelopardalis","content":"*   /In 40,000 years, Voyager 1 will brush past Gliese 445, the star of Camelopardalis. Voyager 1, launched in 1977, is on a trajectory that will take it near the star Gliese 445 in about 40,000 years. Though the spacecraft will be silent by then, its path raises questions about the significance of this encounter. Image 2: The Star in Context. ## The Star in Context. By the time Voyager approaches, the star itself will have moved closer to the solar system, making the passage possible. Image 3: The Distance of the Encounter. ## The Distance of the Encounter. Voyager will not enter the star system directly but will pass within about 1.6 light years. For comparison, the nearest star to the Sun today, Proxima Centauri, is about 4.2 light years away. Image 8: The Legacy of the Fly-by.","score":0.86767644,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://www.iflscience.com/in-40000-years-voyager-1-will-have-a-close-encounter-with-gliese-445-80755","title":"In 40,000 Years, Voyager 1 Will Have A Close Encounter With Gliese 445 | IFLScience","content":"We have emailed you a PDF version of the article you requested. ## In 40,000 Years, Voyager 1 Will Have A Close Encounter With Gliese 445. ## The encounter will not be Voyager's closest, and is far from it's last. In 40,000 years, long after its mission is over, NASA's Voyager 1 spacecraft will have a close encounter with Gliese 445. "It will take about 300 years for Voyager 1 to reach the inner edge of the Oort Cloud and possibly about 30,000 years to fly beyond it.". "It took 35 years to reach interstellar space, but it will take 40,000 years for Voyager 1 to be closer to the star AC +79 3888 than our sun," NASA explains. Gliese 445 is an M-type main-sequence star with around a third of the mass of our Sun. At the moment ,it is around 17,000 light-years from Earth, but by the time the encounter with Voyager happens it will be around 3.5 light-years away from us.","score":0.8506799,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://www.quora.com/When-Voyager-1-in-40-000-years-is-closer-to-Gliese-445-than-the-Sun-will-it-start-to-go-faster-because-of-the-Gravity-from-Gliese-445","title":"When Voyager 1, in 40,000 years, is closer to Gliese 445 than the Sun, will it start to go faster because of the Gravity from Gliese 445?","content":"When Voyager 1, in 40,000 years, is closer to Gliese 445 than the Sun, will it start to go faster because of the Gravity from Gliese 445? It all has to do with Voyager 1 (V1) and Gliese 445’s (G445) paths. It’s true that they will be be fairly close (as stellar distances go) but they’ll still be so far apart (about 1.6 light years at their closest) that G445’s gravitational effect on V1 will be miniscule. I haven’t been able to find a projection of their path’s to tell me that, but basically, no, V1’s speed won’t be significantly affected by G445. The space agency said Voyager 2 will leave the Oort Cloud, "a collection of small objects that are still under the influence of the Sun’s gravity," in approximately 30,000 years, so it is still being influenced by the Sun's gravity to some extent. So no, it won’t be out of the Sun’s gravitational influence for another 30,000 years.","score":0.70847535,"raw_content":null},{"url":"https://www.facebook.com/groups/astronautslife/posts/2937219066453067","title":"Voyager 1 spacecraft to pass near Gliese 445 star in ...","content":"In about 40,000 years, a spacecraft launched by humanity in the 20th century will pass near another star.

